-- 1. [Problem Restatement] Prove that every prime p divides a^p − a for each positive integer a. 2. [Key Idea] In (a + b)^p all interior binomial coefficients are multiples of p, so modulo p the expansion collapses to a^p + b^p; taking b = 1 and iterating yields a^p ≡ a (mod p). 3. [Proof] Binomial-theorem proof Step 1. If p | a the claim is immediate, so assume p∤a. Step 2. For any integers x, y (x + y)^p = Σ_{k=0}^p (p choose k) x^{p−k} y^k. Because p is prime, (p choose k) = p·(p−1)!/(k!(p−k)!) is divisible by p whenever 1 ≤ k ≤ p−1. Hence (x + y)^p ≡ x^p + y^p (mod p). (∗) Step 3. Put x = a and y = 1 in (∗): (a + 1)^p ≡ a^p + 1 (mod p). Step 4. Replace a by a−1, then by a−2, … , and telescope: a^p − (a−1)^p ≡ a − (a−1) (mod p) (a−1)^p − (a−2)^p ≡ (a−1) − (a−2) (mod p) ⋮ 1^p − 0^p ≡ 1 − 0 (mod p). Adding these p congruences gives a^p − 0^p ≡ a − 0 (mod p), i.e. a^p ≡ a (mod p). Thus p divides a^p − a. (Alternate group-theoretic proof) If p | a we are done; otherwise a is a unit modulo p. The multiplicative group (ℤ/pℤ)× has order p−1, so a^{p−1} ≡ 1 (mod p). Multiplying by a gives a^p ≡ a (mod p), hence p | a^p − a. 4. [Conclusion] Therefore, for every prime p and positive integer a, the congruence a^p ≡ a (mod p) holds, i.e. p divides a^p − a.
